Good catch — this looks contradictory until you separate **where** `Date.now()` runs.

## What is bad

```tsx
// ❌ Client — new value on EVERY render
useEffect(() => {
  setShowForm(false);
}, [Date.now()]);
```

Every render calls `Date.now()` again → dependency always “changed” → effect runs again → `setState` → re-render → loop / flaky behavior.

## What we actually do

```ts
// ✅ Server — runs ONCE when the action finishes
return { success: true, nonce: Date.now() };
```

```tsx
// ✅ Client — depends on stored state, not a fresh Date.now()
useEffect(() => {
  if (!createState.nonce) return;
  // ...
}, [createState.nonce, ...]);
```

Here `Date.now()` is **not** in the client dependency array. The client only watches `createState.nonce` — a value that **changes only when the server action returns new state** (once per submit).

| | Server `nonce: Date.now()` | Client `[Date.now()]` |
|---|---|---|
| When it runs | Once per submit | Every render |
| Stored in state? | Yes (`createState.nonce`) | No |
| Safe? | Yes | No |

So we’re not “adding `Date.now()` to dependencies.” We’re using a **timestamp as a one-time completion marker** in action state, because `success: true` alone doesn’t change on the 2nd submit.

`nonce` is just a name for that marker — it could be a counter or UUID; `Date.now()` on the server is a simple way to make each completion unique.

If you want it even clearer in code, you could rename `nonce` to `completedAt` so it’s obvious it’s a stored timestamp, not something recalculated on render. Behavior stays the same.

